Just remember, the one constant in all of your failed relationships is you. You might have had the bad luck to always end up at terrible companies. Or you could be rubbing people the wrong way. It's pretty much impossible to tell from writings on the internet.I will tell you this, I can't remember ever being thrown under a bus by someone who I had a cordial working relationship with. I'm sure at some point I got stabbed in the back by someone who was friendly with me and then went to my boss. But I make a real effort to be friendly and pleasant with people, and it usually results in them giving me the benefit of the doubt. Let me put it this way: you have two competing projects that both want your attention. All other things being equal, you'll probably prioritize the project whose PM is always nice and occasionally brings in donuts over the PM who once yelled at you for something that was really their fault and who never apologized for it. It's the way of the world. So you might as well make it work for you. Ask people about their kids. Talk about last night's baseball game. Bring coffee to a meeting. If you find out you have a common interest with someone, talk about it. If you think maybe you're not communicating well with people, join a group like toast masters. It's quite possible that, because you're always looking for a job when the last one went sour, you're rushing into gigs with terrible corporate cultures. But I see absolutely no harm in working to improve how you relate to your colleagues. Even if you still get thrown under the occasional bus, at least you got to enjoy some coffee and pleasant chit-chat before it happened.This is something that I learned the hard way, BTW. I've always had great rapport with my end users. But I managed to butt heads with my boss at my old job so badly that it was pretty much toxic. I steadfastly maintain that I was totally right about 99% of the time. He had no idea what he was doing. But I handled it badly, and it made my work environment almost unbearable. If I'd worked to preserve our cordial relationship, I think I would have been a lot happier there. And I might have had much better opportunities when I was at that job.
Hopers
Moderator
et Subscriptor
