Hopers wrote:Don't start asking people about their kids just because you need to tick something off on your "I'm a good coworker" checklist. I disagree. I think you should make an effort to be social even if you have no desire to do so. Personally, I don't care at all about my coworkers' kids or about who's getting traded in the NFL. But I still ask people how their kids are doing or what they think of the home team. My coworkers know full well I'm not interested in these topics, but they appreciate that I'm asking. Since I started doing this, people like me better and I get my way more often. I can see a clear causal connection between "Will the Dolphins make the playoffs? Does your daughter still have the flu?" and "Thanks for accepting my project and supporting me with upper management."
