PastorOfMuppets wrote:The instances where I had a knife thrown in my back were with other silos in the organization. One instance was one group was developing a cadillac product, our group was tasked with developing a cost sensitive product. The tech lead of the cadillac product wanted us to reuse the work they had done. I evaluated it and it was too costly to use because our product was cost sensitive. During that time the company was being acquired and re-orgs were happening, people were making political moves and unwilling to really stick their necks out. While the PM and rest of team agreed with me but I was the one that had to defend the decision to senior management. After a month of meetings on the issue without resolve, I quit taking 2 coworkers with me to a new job.What was your relationship between yourself and the tech lead of the cadillac product before everything went down?When and how did you decline to use the cadillac product? Was this in front of members of the cadillac group and senior members of management? Or was this in a private discussion with the tech lead? Or somewhere in between?It's likely that while the company was being acquired, members of the cadillac product group felt they needed to show new management that their product was IMPORTANT AND POPULAR within the company. That may be why you were asked to use their product. They may have felt threatened by your refusal to cooperate with their request and thus fear and hate lead to the dark side.One possible strategy is to publicly praise but always claim lack of bandwidth to integrate the production at this time. If you truly thought the cadillac product was inappropriate, you keep delaying and praising until the crisis passes.
