Here's a good case study for you:There's a guy in our office who isn't in my direct line of command, but he is in a position of authority. He's not my boss, but he can give me projects to work on, and he's usually the one who sends us home early the day before a long weekend. Yesterday, he was flapping around the office, wringing his hands over finding the stuff he needed to work from home today. The weather was supposed to be nasty (and it sure is).Now, the thing is, this guy works a job that he *can* do remotely, which I can't do. And he's definitely higher up in the food chain. So, he was technically correct in getting his ducks together and then heading out. But.... it definitely rubbed everyone else in the office the wrong way. He very much had the attitude of taking care of himself, and not caring about anyone else's safety (he has the easiest/safest commute out of any of us). If he'd said, "let's stay in touch tomorrow in case the weather gets bad" or even just said to drive safe, it would have been no big deal. Instead, he came across as a self-centered douche. It was very much an attitude of "well, I'm going to stay safe, screw all of you." I'm a big girl, I know it's my job to drive in unless the governor declares a state of emergency. That's why I have snow tires. But when a coworker acts like his own concerns trumps everybody else, people notice.You can be 100% right about something and still have everyone shaking their heads about you.
