Quote:I'd also say, in general, try to be happy and not take anything personally. Smile a lot. Pretty much everyone likes happy, smiley people. Finally, take care of yourself. Healthy people earn more, are promoted more and are hired more.In a regular environment, stay positive, smile, find out how to relate to the people you work with, and whose opinions affect your work. Maybe that's the dreaded small talk. Or maybe that's just checking in on a regular schedule to discuss the state of affairs.In a political environment, be proactive about managing your resources and do some 'walking around' where you sync up with important people and what they are thinking. If you had found out that a rival was trying to affect your project plan earlier, you would have had a better chance at damage control. Maybe even going to the guy directly and coming to a compromise of sorts. It's still not too late to go to that guy and discuss how to build the cheaper version with the resources available. Although you may have to swallow some pride and take a few aspirin for the b*tt-hurt. If you read about how managers and directors in highly effective environments like Apple and Google, you will find there is a lot of walking around and talking, building communications networks and resource allies. That's not to say that everything is peachy, but there is a give and a take.
